VVirtuosic recital
p3
sVnews
p4
VVisakha Music and Dance Academy featured a veena recital by U.S.-based Rajeswari Pariti. The concert organised last Monday at Kalabharathi had its mridangam teacher of its School of Music and Dance, G. Venkata Rao along with noted S. Hanumantha Rao from Tadepalligudem on ghatam. They provided rhythmical support effectively.She stands known like her three brothers and two sisters for innate relish and imbibed style of playing on veena by their father Ayyagari Someswara Rao. He was known for his amazingly unique ambidexterity playing on the veena. He evolved it and established himself for the exquisitely evocative exposition of the entirety of Carnatic music.Rajeswari going revelatory of these reminiscences, rendered a pleasing and eruditely exploring recital. Improving innovatively and gradually going exalted starting with the Aditaala Saveri Varnam, rendered the Natakeerthana Swaminatha followed by elaborated versions of Paridanamichite (Bilahari), Neevallagunadoshamemi (Kapi) and a composition of Annamayya.The highlight of the evening then came in the form of Ragam Tanam and Pallavi was set in Dharmavathi. The pallavi was set in Chaturasragathi in Aditalam with two letters gap. After elaborate alapana, she rendered Thanam in Ragamalika (Ghanaragapanchakam). Then, she rendered the pallavi Sree Lalitha Sivapriye Sannuthe Devi, Brovave Amba and concluded with eruditely sparkling swarakapalana in ragamalika in Hindolam, Sivaranjani, Revathi and so on also along with gathi bhedam. The Thani on mridangam and ghatam went scintillating. The concert concluded on a devoutly brisk note with the rendering of Annamayya's Narayanathe Namo Namo.
